<h3>B. Write the meaning and world class of the following words. Then use them in   sentences of your own.</h3>
<p>implore, despair, beseech, eloquent, whirl, egoism, agony, delirious, delusive,
    compensate, mortgage, brood, prelude
    </p>
<pre>
    Implore (verb):	beg someone earnestly or desperately to do something.
                I implore mercy from them.
    Despair (noun):	The feeling of having lost all hope (hopelessness) 
                His speech was full of self-hatred and despair.
    Beseech (verb):	to ask somebody to do in an anxious way (implore/beg) 
                Let her go, I beseech you.
    Eloquent (adjective):able to express a feeling adjectives. Her silence was more eloquent than words.
    
    Whirl (noun):A movement of something turning round and round / a state of confusion.
                I don't understand what he said, my head was in a whirl. 
    Egoism (noun):Thinking that you are better or more important than anyone else.
                I hate people who shows their egoism in completion of task. 
    Agony (noun):great pain or suffering after a long walk she feels agony on her feet.
                She has agony on her feet because of long walking.
    Delirious (adj):unable to think or speak in sensible and reasonable way
                I was delirious and blacked out several times.
    Delusive (adj):giving a false or misleading impression 
                It was a delusive victory.
    Compensate (verb):to remove or reduce the bad effect of something. 
                His willingness to work hard compensated for his lack of skill
    Mortgage (verb):To make subject to a claim or risk pledge against a doubtful outcome
                A mortgage that secures debt incurred in connection with the property.
    Brood (noun):a large family of chicken
                He grew up among a lively brood of brothers and sisters.
    Prelude(N):	an action or event that happens before another more important one and forms an introduction to it
                A ceasefire had been agreed as a prelude to full peace negotiations.
    
</pre>
