    <h3>B. What is the difference among transitive, intransitive and linking verbs? Give
        examples of each.
    </h3>
    <p>A transitive verb requires an object to complete its meaning</p>
    <li>I write a poem</li>
    <li>My father raise cattle</li>
    <p>Write and raise are transitive verb they have direct object to complete the meaning a poem and cattle.</p>
    <h3>Intransitive verb</h3>
    <p>
        An-intransitive verb doesn't require an object to complete its meaning. <br>
        She feels sad. <br>
        He sneered loudly. <br>
        I don't understand her feelings.<br>
    </p>
    <h3>Linking verb</h3>
    <p>
        A linking verb links a subject with its predicate<br>
        The children are smart.
    </p>
    <h3>The cake smells good</h3>
    <p>The most common links verbs are:</p>
    <p>is/am/are/was/were/become/seem/look, smell, touch appear, sound, taste/feel etc</p>
    <p>
        (i) The hungry lion roars - intransitive <br>
        (ii) The weather and again – Intransitive <br>
        (iii) The weather is hot - linking <br>
        (iv) Owls hide in the daytime -intransitive
    </p>
    <p><strong>Community forest in Nepal</strong></p>
    <p>
        The community forestry program in Nepal is a government effort to reduce forest degradation and promote
        sustainable forestry practices as well as to improve the livelihood of the community. It incorporates distinct
        policies, Institutions and practices. The two main goals of the community forestry program is to empower local
        communities whilst encouraging environmental conservation benefits of the Himalayan forest.<br><br> Nepal has
        become one of the first developing nations to adopt a community forestry management program which gives
        authority and groups to manage the forest resources. As a result, Nepal now stands as one of the leaders in
        community based forest management. They have made direct progress in halting environmental degradation and by
        regenerating forests in barren areas. Studies have proven the potential benefits that community forestry will
        have in combating environmental degradation as well as utilizing resources in sufficient manner.<br><br> One of
        the two main goals under the community forest was to alleviate poverty as well as improve general livelihoods of
        the Nepal people. Various forms of discrimination on the basis of caste, economic status ethnicity, gender, age
        and vulnerability exist in Nepalese society, The key objective of this program was to increase the participation
        and empower the socially marginalized people allowing decision making abilities within the communities.<br><br>
        Now 1.6 million households are included as a community forest user group there are 19.000 community forest user
        groups. These groups are utilizing the forest resources, such as, fuel wood, timber fodder, herbal medicine,
        building materials manure from the forest. They make their own rules and regulations to manage the forest
        resources. Each and every household family equally get facility from it.<br><br> Community forestry is a
        participatory forest management system in Nepal that was started in the late 1970s. Gilmour and fisher (1991)
        defined community forestry as the control, protection, and management of forest resources by rural communities
        for whom trees and forests are an integral part of their meaning.
    </p>
