    <h2>Comprehension</h2>
    <h3>Answer these questions</h3>
    <h3>a. What were the restrictions imposed on the Blacks in South Africa?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Racial segregation, political and economic restrictions were imposed on the Blacks in South
        Africa.</p>
    <h3>b. Why was Mandela arrested?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Mandela was arrested because he was charged with organising an armed wind of ANC. In this
        regard, he was penalized for his protests.</p>
    <h3>c. How did he describe racism and racial oppression?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>He described racism and racial oppression as the pernicious ideology and practice.</p>
    <h3>d. Why did the thank all the international guests?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>He thanked all the international guests for having come to take possession with the people
        of his country in their victory against injustice.</p>
    <h3>e. Why did he think that people in his country had achieved political emancipation?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>He thought that people in his country had achieved political emancipation to liberate
        themselves from the continuing ndage of poverty, deprivation, suffering gender and other discrimination.</p>
    <h3>f. What is the main point of Mandela's speech? </h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>The main point of Mandela's speech is that freedom is a right of all the people by birth
        and no one should try to take it away from them. He asks people of south Africa to build a society where there
        will be justice, peace, right and equality for all people</p>
    <h2>Critical thinking</h2>
    <h3>a. What does Mandela mean when he says-a rainbow nation peace with itself and the world?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Through the expression u rainbow nation at peace with itself and the world'. Mandela means
        the unity of multiculturalism. Moreover, he intends to signify the coming together of people from many different
        nations, to the country once recognized with the division of white and black under the Apartheid rule, Rainbow
        is the combination of seven colors. South Africa is referred to a rainbow Nation to describe the unity of
        various cultural, racial, ethnic groups. In some south African cultures, the rainbow symbolizes hope and bright
        future.<br><br>
        Mandela anticipates his nation as the peaceful place where they could build the society in which all south
        Africans, both black and white, could live without any fear in their hearts and with absolute right to human
        dignity. He wants them to live and work together in unity like the band of colours in rainbow. He wishes them to
        forget the vicious and repressive past.
    </p>
    <h3>b. Mandela should have avenged those who imprisoned him for such a long period. Instead, he followed the path of
        reconciliation. Why do you think he did so?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Nelson Mandela was a man who cherished the ideal of free society all of his life. He fought
        against the white dominations upon the blacks in South Africa Moreover, he fought for democracy thereby ensuring
        all racial and cultural groups could live together in harmony with equal opportunity. He was an empathetic and
        forgiving leader. As a man in search for excellence, Mandela felt the absence of bitterness and vengeance in
        him. The moral leader and democratic hero believed in liberty and justice throughout his life. He asked his
        people to forget the past and forgive the tormentors. His composed. dignified and peace-loving disposition was
        the reason he undertook the path of reconciliation.</p>
    <h3>c. Why and how have societies struggled with segregation in the world? Do you find any evidence of segregation
        in your society? Discuss.</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Segregation is the social separation of human beings on the basis of a number of factors,
        including race, ethnicity or nationality. This term is usually used to describe a condition of inequality Many
        societies have struggled with this problem in the world. Racial segregation is one of the most common forms of
        segregation. It is constitutionally forbidden all over the world. However, it still manages to survive through
        social norms and practices. Racial segregation has appeared in all parts of the world where there are
        multiracial communities. Having said that, we can't turn a blind eye to segregation lews, homosexuals, females,
        marginalized groups and so on.<br><br>
        The constitution of Nepal doesn't endure any segregation in terms of religion, caste and ethnicity. However,
        untouchability, racial discrimination, gender inequality is still prevalent in our society.<br><br>
        Marginalized social groups are still kept at an arm's length from policy
        Poverty-based segregation is also prominent in our country.
    </p>
    <h2>Writing</h2>
    <h3>a. Nepal has topsy-turvy political history. Many changes have been observed in different times. Write a short
        biography of any Nepali freedom fighter incorporating the changes brought under his/her leadership.</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Girija Prasad Koirala is a famous name in Nepalese history and politics. He was born on 4
        July 1924. Affectionately called Girija Babu, he headed Nepali Congress and served as the prime minister of
        Nepal on four occasions: from 1991 to 1994, 1998 to 1999, 2000 to 2001 and from 2006 to 2008. He was the acting
        head of state of Nepal between January 2007 and July 2008 when the country. transitioned from monarchy to a
        republic.<br><br>
        Koirala who was active in politics for over sixty years. He was a pioneer of the Nepalese labour movement,
        having started the first political workers' movement (the Biratnagar Jute Mill Strike) in Nepal. In 1991, he
        became the first democratically checked prime minister since 1959, when his brother B.P. Koirala and Nepali
        congress party were brought into power in the country's first democratic election.
    </p>
    <h3>b. Do you think there is racial/caste related discrimination in our country? Discuss with your friend: Write a
        five-minute speech.</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>The government of Nepal has repeatedly expressed a commitment to eliminate caste and racial
        based discrimination from the country. However, these discriminatory practices are still prevalent in our
        country as they find their roots in culture and tradition. The so-called untouchable castes are the subjects of
        continuous torture and oppression at the hand of the privileged groups. For instance, Dalit women are extremely
        vulnerable to sexual exploitation. Among them, Badi and landless groups are forced to survive by means of flesh
        trade. Although they don't want to, poverty, and social stigmatization make them bound to pursuit. Moreover,
        they are routinely refused entry into public temples, tea shops, public wells and taps. They are denied the
        right to sell milk and open tea-shops. Most seriously, their right to marry with free consent is also withheld.
        Political leaders are using the issues of the marginalized caste groups for their own benefits. They promise to
        eliminate the caste discrimination and ensure equity and human dignity. However, these vows are merely
        restricted to the words rather than actions.<br><br>
        Caste-based discrimination must be treated as a matter of requiring the introduction and effective
        implementation of laws that will hold the perpetrators of abuses responsible for their actions. It is an
        imperative to ensure adequate compensation for the victims. Strong laws should be drafted against the
        discriminatory tendencies.
    </p>
    <h2>Grammar</h2>
    <h2>Should and had better</h2>
    <h3>A. Look at these examples.</h3>
    <img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/iampokharasahitey/englishapp/main/11English_chapter9_3.JPG">
    <p>
        <strong>'Should' is used to give advice and suggestions</strong><br>
        1. My brother told me he is on his way. He should be here soon.<br>
        2. You are late again. You should have arrived here before 15 minutes. <br>
        3. You should go to a cozy restaurant if you want to get real flavour.<br><br>

        'Had better' is used to give strong advice with bad consequence (warning)<br><br>
        i. You had better not sleep late because you have an exam tomorrow.<br>
        ii. She had better not be late again, or she'll miss her bus.<br>
        iii. It's cold day, you'd better wear warm clothes before going outside, or you'll catch a cold.
    </p>
    <h3>B. Complete the sentences with should or shouldn't. Use one of these verbs.</h3>
    <table>
        <tr>
            <td>drink&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; visit&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; leave
                &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; roam&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp; quit</td>
        </tr>
    </table>
    <p>
        a. You have really done a wonderful job. I recommend you <u>shouldn't quit</u> it. <br><br>
        b. That's a very dangerous area. Tourists <u>shouldn't visit </u>there.<br><br>
        c. I'm going to be late. Do you think I <u>should leave </u>now?<br><br>
        d. Children <u>shouldn't drink</u> sugary drinks. It's not very healthy.<br><br>
