<h2>Comprehension</h2>
<h3>Answer these questions</h3>
<h3>a.	Where was Napoleon from?</h3>
<p>Ans.	He was from Corsica, France.</p>
<h3>b.	Why did poor and middle-class people declare France a republic?</h3>
<p>Ans.	Poor and middle-class people declared France a republic by overthrowing monarchy because they were tired of paying heavy taxes to the government. They wanted liberty, democracy and pay taxes according to their wealth.</p>
<h3>c.	When did Napoleon declare himself emperor of France? </h3>
<p>Ans.	Napoleon declared himself emperor of France in 1804.</p>
<h3>d. What did he do when he ruled France? </h3>
<p>Ans.	He restored law and order after the revolution in France. He built many fine roads and improved the old ones. He turned Paris into a beautiful city with wide streets, fine bridges, and beautiful buildings and monuments. Most important of all, he improved law and system in France.</p>
<h3>e.	Which countries did he rule when he was the emperor? </h3>
<p>Ans.	Napoleon ruled Italy, Switzerland, and Germany when he was the emperor.</p>

<h3>f.	What was the main cause of his destruction? </h3>
<p>Ans.	His invasion of Russia in 1812 (being driven by lust for power) was the main cause of his destruction.</p>
<h3>g.	How did his rule as emperor end in Europe?</h3>
<p>
    Ans.	In 1812, Napoleon made his biggest mistake by invading Russia. He entered Moscow, but he found that nearly all the people had left. There were fires all over the city, and most of it was destroyed. With no place to house his soldiers and no food for them to eat in the bitter Russian winter, Napoleon had no choice but to retreat. Napoleon lost half a million men in Russia. Resultantly, he became powerless and was overthrown from power.
    </p>
<h3>h.	How could Napoleon have been an even greater ruler?</h3>
<p>Ans.	Napoleon could have been even greater ruler if he had not been driven by his love of power. He should have been satisfied with whatever land he had won.</p>

<h2>Critical thinking</h2>
<h3>a.	What can be the qualities of a great leader? Can a great leader remain in
    power for long in a country? Discuss.
    </h3>
<p>Ans.	John Calvin Maxwell, an American author, speaker, and pastor, once famously remarked: "A leader knows the way, goes the way and shows the way". In a brief statement, Mr. Maxwell has given a voluminous description of an adept leader. A good leader creates an inspiring vision of the failure and motivates, inspires people to engage with that vision. He manages delivery of the vision as well as coaches. and builds a team so that it is more effective to achieve the vision. He must have vision and ability to convert that vision to others. H will be able to think critically about the organization, team work and understand the strengths and weakness and correction time.
    If a leader does not get driven by his love of power, he can remain in power for a long time. He should be humble to his people. He must be engrossed in the service of the subjects of his care. He should not be ruled by arrogance, greed and impatience.
    </p>
<h3>b.	The 16th president of the USA, Abraham Lincoln said democracy is government of the people for the people and by the people. Do you think it is perfectly applicable in the present context of Nepal? Explain. </h3>
<p>Ans.	Democracy was rightfully defined as a rule of the people for the people by the people', by a popular freedom fighter, Abraham Lincoln. I don't think it is perfectly applicable in the present context of Nepal. One can argue that this country is now at democratic republic. However, all democracies may not have been properly. upholding Mr. Lincoln's view. In my view, assurance of some basic democratic principles is a must to maintain people's rule. Recognition of the fundamental dignity of every person is the first requirement. Similarly, respecting for the equality of all persons is another characteristic of a democratic culture, which will be joined by civil liberties, such as freedom of speech, expression, etc., and rule of law.
    But in the Nepalese context, fundamental rights of the commoners have been massively ignored. Civil liberties are manipulated according to the will of the leaders and the power holders. Majority group suppresses the minority one. Class and caste division is still in practice. Social injustice, inequality, unemployment and political instability regularly invades Nepal amidst the endless conflicts between the ruler party and the opposition parties. Nepalese version of democracy then goes like this: 'Democracy is the rule of the leader by the leader for the leader.'
    </p>

<h2>Writing</h2>
<h3>a.	Write an essay on Power and Politics in about 500 words.</h3>
<p>Ans.	Politics and power are interrelated concepts. Where there is politics there is power. We can put it this way, politics is an activity related to power. The former is the possession and the distribution of power. It is often said that political power is the greatest power of all.</p>

<p>Power is the ability to influence the behavior of others to get what you want. It is frequently defined as the ability to influence the behavior of others with or without resistance. It is often visible to others within organizations (for instance, politics). It has both positive and negative consequences. It can be intoxicating and equally devastating when abused. It may derive from a number of sources, including social class (material wealth can equal power), resource currency (material items such as money, property, food), personal or group charisma, ascribed power (acting on perceived or assumed abilities, whether these bear testing or not), social influence. of tradition (compare ascribed power), etc.</p>

<p>In simple words, politics is the way that people living in groups make decisions. Moreover, it is about making agreements between people so that they can live. together in groups such as tribes, cities, or countries. In this regard, politics is at the heart of all collective social activities that involve collaborative decisions. It is the interest of both individuals and groups.</p>

<p>Politics is usually applied to behaviour within civil governments, but it can be observed in all human group interactions, including corporate, academic, and religious institutions. We will focus primarily on political power in this essay. Some define politics quite simply as the exercise of power. It often involves the distribution of resources or decisions on who gets what". It can be seen as a game in which actors try to influence each other to get others to do what they. would not otherwise have done. However, it can also include less observable ways of exercising power such as the setting of agendas - be it parliamentary agendas that determine who gets to speak, for how long and on what issues, or news agendas that determine which issues are newsworthy and will appear on the evening news, and which issues will not make the cut.</p>

<h3>b.	Write a couple of paragraphs about a national hero who fought bravely in the Anglo-Nepal War.</h3>

<p>Ans.	Bhakti Thapa was a brave soldier. When we talk about the Anglo-Nepal War, we cannot skip the reference of this heroic man. Just two years later after the unification of Jumla, he was made the supreme commander (Sardar) of the Nepalese army and stationed to the west of capital in the region that stretched almost up to the Sutlej River. He was the patriot involved in the Anglo-Nepal war. His most important contribution in the war was at the western front of Deothal.</p>
<p>In the Anglo-Nepal war, sardar Bhakti Thapa was controlling operation of the whole western region of Nepal from the fort of Malaun. As the British forces had controlled over the fort of Deuthal 1,000 m away from Malaun fort the whole of the western region was stake, which made sardar Bhakti Thapa go to the battle field taking naked Khukuri and sword on his hand along with 2,000 Nepalese Solders. amidst the fierce gun firing of the British Army on April 16, 1815. There was fiere fighting between the two forces killing 100 soldiers of the Nepalese army while all the officers were killed except only one arsenal. In this battle when sardar Bhakti Thapa tried to capture British cannon, he was hit by the bullet at his heart. The major David Octorlony, handed over very respectfully to the Nepalese army.</p>
<P>The dead body of Bhakti Thapa after covering it with Dosalla (Woolen shawl) The very next day, his body was cremated with due state guard of honour. His two wives committed sati. Before going to the battle field. He had handed over his son Buda Kaji Amar Singh Thapa. Sitting at the foot of the flag of Nepal. Bada Kaji Amar Singh Thapa and Ram Das, the son of Bhakti Thapa encouraged the Nepalese army looking around the sight of war. The anglo Nepal was took a different turn after. He end of this battle. The way sardar Bhakti Thapa laid down his life at the Deothal battle has become a legend in Nepalese history.</P>
<p>Bhakti Thapa, then 74. led a daring counterattack against the British force entrenched at Deothal. He had played a significant role to keep Nepal alive.</p>

<h2>Grammar</h2>
<p>may, might, must, can't</p>
<h3>A.	Study the following sentences.</h3>
<pre>
a.She may/might be in France.
b.You've had a long journey. You must be tired.
c.Niraj can't be in Gorkha - I saw him this morning.
    We use <strong>may</strong> or <strong>might</strong> to talk about the possibility of something in the present 
    or in the future. 
    We use <strong>must </strong>and <strong>can't</strong> to express certainty in the present.
</pre>

<h3>B.	Fill in the blanks with may, must or can't.</h3>
<p>
    <ol>
        <li>Matthew <u>must </u>be at home. I can see his bike in front of his home.</li>
        <li>They <u>may</u> be coming tomorrow.</li>
        <li>She <u>can't</u> speak French very well. She's only lived in Paris for two weeks.</li>
        <li>My key is not in my pocket or on my desk so it <u>must</u> be in the drawer.</li>
        <li>I saw him yesterday. He <u>can't </u>be abroad.</li>
        <li>You got the job? That's great. You <u>must</u> be very delighted.</li>
        <li>I <u>may</u> finish it by tomorrow if I stay at work all night, but I'm not sure.</li>
        <li>Somebody is knocking on the door. It <u>must </u>be Sabina-she promised to come today.</li>
        </ol>
</p>

<h3>C.	Rewrite the following sentences using may/might, must or can't.</h3>

<p>Example: May be they went away. 
   <br> They may/might have gone away.
 </p>

<pre>
a.  I'm sure he's not going to the cinema today.
Ans. He can't be going to the cinema today. 
b.  Perhaps she knows the answer.
Ans. She may know the the answer.
c.  I'm sure he has a car. 
Ans. He must have a car.
d.  I doubt if it rains later on.
Ans. It can't rain later on.
e.  Perhaps she wants to be alone. 
Ans. She might want to be alone.
f.  I'm sure Harina is in her office.
Ans. Harina must be in her office.
        
</pre>

