    <h2>Comprehension</h2>
    <h3>Answer these questions.</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>a.	What's the difference between the body and the soul?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Man consists of a soul and body, that the body is in time and space, but the soul is in time only. Abstract soul stays in a physical body. Body is physical structure made of flesh, bones, and blood. Soul is the abstract and more often spiritual concept believed to have existed even after the death of a body.<br><br>
        <strong>b. 	What do you understand by the psychologists saying that there is no such thing as mind?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The psychologists theory states that conscious mental state must be among the contents of working memory. The user interface of our mind is available to other functions such as decision making and verbalization. They are not in working memory nor are we directly aware of them. Mind is and occurrence. Mental activity reduces everything to the bodily functions. Mind orders to do the activity before our physical organs get ready to come in action.<br><br>
        <strong>c.	How can a mental activity be reduced to a physical activity? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Physical activity and mental stimulation are both considered vital for keeping ourselves active in our life. There are various difficulties in the way of reducing mental activity to physical activity, Daily exercises, like jogging swimming. cycling, gardening, dancing, doing yoga and meditation, have been proved to reduce anxiety and depression. The modern would be materialist thus finds himself in a curious position that for a while, he may, with a certain degree of success. reduce the activities of the mind to those of the body. The scientists cannot explain the fact that the body itself is merely a convenient concept invented by the mind.<br><br>
        <strong>d.	How are mind and body related?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The mind-body connection is the link a person's thoughts, attitudes, and behaviors and their physical health. While scientists have long understood that our emotions can affect our bodies, we're just now beginning to understand how emotions influence health and longevity. The mind and body are connected through neural pathways made up of neurotransmitters, hormones and chemicals. <br><br>
        These pathways transmit signals between the body and the brain to control our everyday functions, from breathing, digestion and pain sensations to movement, thinking and feeling. 
        <br><br>
        <strong>e.	What is the relation between mind and memory? Does memory survive a person's death?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Memory, the biologically encoded information, is the long lasting and stable change that is caused by learning through the series of experiments on target memory recall. The essential characteristic of mind is memory, and there is no reason whatever to suppose that the memory associated with a person survives after that person's death. <br><br>
        Memory clearly connected with a certain kind of brain structure is decayed at death. There is every reason to support that memory also ceases. If a person dies, all supportive parts of memory decay and there remains no any medium to transform the message to the brain. So, any experience recollected in the past can't be recalled by the brain after a person's death.
        <br><br>
        <strong>f.	How is our power on the earth's surface entirely dependent upon the sun? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>We cannot do anything whatever to the sun or moon or even to the interior of the earth. We could hardly realize our situation if the sun grew cold. Without the sun's. heat and light the Earth would be lifeless ball of ice coated rock. The son warms our seas, stirs our atmosphere, generates our weather patterns and gives energy to the growing green plants that provide the food and oxygen for life on earth. If there is any truth in modem physics, more particularly in the second law of thermodynamics, we can't hope that the human race will continue forever.<br><br>
    </p>
    <h2>Critical thinking</h2>
    <p>
        <strong>a.	Do you believe that soul really exists? Write your arguments in support of your answer.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The belief that souls exist and humans have them enjoys near unanimous support in the general population. It is one of the most contentious issues among philosophers and scientists, however. Many philosophers and scientists reject the soul hypothesis to consider what the nonexistence of the soul would entail. <br><br>
        It is important to note that the soul is not merely the mind. Although soul believers may equal soul with minds, one can believe in mind without believing in souls. For example one can believe that the mind is something other than the brain, but also maintain that all mental activity is dependent upon brain activity. Belief in soul requires one to believe that mental activity is separable from the brain-which it can continue without the brain. Unlike belief in souls belief in existence of minds is still the norm in most academic circle. If the soul pre-exists the body, it is reasonable to assume that it exists after death as well. The belief that the soul continues its existence after the death of the body is a matter of philosophical or theological speculation rather than that of a simple faith.
        <br><br>
        <strong>b.	If you want to change your body, you first have to change your mind. Discuss. </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>If we want to change our body, we need to start with the mind. The first step to any change in life starts with our mindset. Mind is considered to function as a commanding force to hold power of controlling our bodily actions. In other words, actions are the bodily manifestations of the commands of the mind. For example, scientists have discovered the facts that constant worry and stress over jobs, finances, or other problems can cause tense muscles, pain, headaches, and stomach problems. It may also lead to high blood pressure or other serious problems. These problems can far be reduced in our bodies by keeping our mind free from tensions and anxieties.<br><br>
    </p>
    <h2>Writing</h2>
    <h3>Write Critically on the following topics</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>a. The existance of god</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Opinions relating in favour of and in opposition to the existence of god have been controversial from many years and anticipated by philosophers, theologians, scientists, and others. The discussion with reference to the existence of god is very traditional and one of the most argued subjects in human history. <br><br>
        The perception of God normally relates to a monotheistic, superlative, eventual and personal being. This view is mostly originated from Christian and Hebrew traditions. Traditional view Portrayed God as having perfections in everything. Many religions and different societies believe that God is a body that can't be defined. Some traditional approaches defined God as "the prime mover" or the uncaused cause, the ultimate creator or a being nothing greater than which can be conceived. <br><br>
        Most schools of Hinduism believe that there is existence of god but some of them don't believe that. Law of Karma provides basis of the existence of God. They believe that the action of Karma is not performed by human's self, there must be existence of God to control and monitor all Karmas (actions). They also believe that fruit of Karma is transferred and dispensed through a body that is known as God and thus proves the existence. <br><br>
        The disapproving argument claims that there is no visible God. There is no any reason to believe that there is a God. If somebody calls God in danger & crisis and he/she achieves something or gets the idea to solve the problem, its existence could be considered valid But believing in God's existence people have morality, faith and harmony to human nature . <br><br>
        <br><br>
        <strong>b.	Religion influences ethics and morality</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Ethics and morality relate to "right" and "wrong" conduct. While they are i sometimes used interchangeably, they are different ethics refer to rules provided by an external source, e.g., codes of conduct in workplaces or principles in religions. Morality often refers to an individual's own principles regarding right and wrong. <br><br>
        Often, religion and ethics are treated as the same thing, with various religions making claims about their belief systems being the best way for people to live actively and try to convert unbelievers. Not all religions are the same, some are more liberal than others and some more conservative, but in general, all religious traditions believe that their faith represents a path to enlightenment and salvation. <br><br>
        By contrast, ethics are universal decision-making tools that may be used by a person of any religious belief and even an atheist. While religion makes claims about cosmology, social behaviour, and the proper treatment of others, ethics are based on logic and reason rather than tradition or injunction. <br><br>
        <br><br>
    </p>
