    <h2>Comprehension</h2>
    <h3>Answer the following questions.</h3>
    <h3>a. Why did millions of Palestinians leave their country?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Millions of Palestinians left their country because they were denied basic human rights. To
        find better life and better economic opportunities, they left their home country.</p>
    <h3>b. How is the global culture formed? Is cultural identity possible even in the global culture? Justify.</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Technological advancement, social media, trans-national corporations participate in
        providing a catalyst to form the new dynamics of global culture. It is because no institution, government, group
        or people can clinically separate the new generation from the huge wave of technological advancement, social
        media and cross-cultural behaviourism.</p>
    <h3>c. Why can moving from one side of the world to the other be an economic challenge for newcomers?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>The immigrants arrive in a new land by leaving their ancestral homeland. In this movement,
        they face linguistic and cultural differences which might make it very difficult for them to find jobs. This, in
        turn, might lead the immigrants to economic hardships.</p>
    <h3>d. How can immigrants foster an economy at different magnitudes of scale in their new homes?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Many immigrants start their own business in their new homes. Small entrepreneurs set up
        small shops to sell their traditional cultural products in the new places of settlement. Apart from this, many
        Multinational Corporations and businesses are also established depending upon the labour force based on the
        immigrants. These new arrivals are both prepared and equally motivated to work far harder than usual to make
        their life more comfortable. This hardworking trend evidently enhances the economy of the country hosting the
        immigrants.</p>
    <h3>e. Can immigrants fully integrate in the new societies? Give reasons.</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>No, it's not fully possible for the immigrants to integrate in the new societies since the
        hosts do not open their doors to allow the new comers cultures: integrate into their.</p>
    <h3>f. Mention any two benefits of integrating into a new society for the immigrants.</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Two benefits of integrating into new societies are:<br>
        (i) Economic opportunities<br>
        (ii) Adoption of new ways of thinking and doing works.
    </p>
    <h3>g. Why should the immigrants run in concordance with global culture?</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>The immigrants should run in concordance with global culture to prevent the loss of their
        cultural and societal identities</p>
    <h2>Critical thinking</h2>
    <h3>a. Do you think that the local is globalised and the global is localised? Can there be the global culture as
        well? Give examples.</h3>
    <p><strong>Ans: </strong>Globalization is the word used to describe the growing interdependence of the world's
        economics, cultures, and populations, brought about by cross-border trade in goods and services, technology, and
        flows of investment, people, and information. In contrast, localization is considered as the process of
        preventing the movement of people, goods, information, norms, practices, and institutions outside those specific
        boundaries.<br><br>
        Globalisation and localisation are interrelated terms. They get their meanings in the presence of each other.
        Sometimes, the local can be globalised and the global can be localized. The world has literally grown to be a
        global village. That is to say we are adopting global culture even without our knowledge. For example, Denim (a
        jenns brand of Italian and French origin) is now popularly worn by the youths across the globe.
    </p>
