<h2>Comprehension</h2>
<h2>Answer these questions</h2>
<h3>a.	How did the author feel when she saw a colourful rooster in the western Himalayas?</h3>
<p>Ans.	The author felt warmly welcomed by nature when she saw a colourful rooster in the western Himalayas.</p>
  <h3>b.	How does she describe the houses on the trails of western Nepal? </h3>

<p>Ans.	According to her, stone houses held themselves together under a rock, above a river, looking too crumbly to live in.</p>
<h3>c.	What does she mean when she says "I walked towards a village15 kilometres further as the crow flies?"</h3>

<p>Ans.	By this expression, she means that she was very tired, she couldn't walk fast and the village was till 15 kilometres away.</p>

<h3>d.	Describe the village Thankur in brief.</h3>

<p>Ans.	Thankur had only two houses. One could not see much life in this dry region. The author could only see 3 monals there.</p>

<h3>e.	What happened when she reached Jumla and how was she relieved?</h3>

<p>Ans.	When she reached Jumla, she was ill with an unknown virus and bad tummy. An American she met in a hotel gave her medicine. The Pani puri at a local catery also helped in her recovery.</p>

<h3>f.	How does the author describe the bucket water in Khali Lagna?</h3>

<p>Ans.	The author describes the bucket water Khali Lagna as chilling and frozen. However, her surprise knew no bounds as she found lukewarm water after cracking the icicles.</p>

<h3>g.	How was Rara Lake on the day she reached there?</h3>

<p>Ans.	According to the writer, Himalaya was glistening it its dark blue glory in the biggest freshwater lake of Nepal. Moreover, the magnificent sky-scraping pine trees decorated the ground with giant pine cones: Coots glided over very crystal clear water. It was panoramic and soothing.</p>

<h2>Critical thinking</h2>

<h3>a.	It is said that travelling a place equals to reading three books. Do you agree? Why?</h3>
<P>Ans.	I strongly agree this statement. We can learn many things from both reading and travelling. One can enrich his/her understanding of cultures and places through both of the ventures. However, travelling is more alluring when it comes to learning and understanding. For instance, unlike reading a book, it facilitates self-observation. We learn the things we see more comprehensibly than reading in books.
    Books only give us a general view about the subject of place. It provides us with a one side judgement about something and, in the process, misguides us. In contrast, visiting a place eliminates such prejudices: Similarly, reading bores us whereas travelling keeps entertained and engaged. By nature, our mind catches interesting and attractive insights faster. Books dictate us about the unknown whereas travels take us there. In this regard, both are some sorts of journey, only ere. divergence is that travelling is livelier and funnier. 
    </P>

<h3>b.	The author spent five-week long walk along the western Himalayas. Do you think it was adventurous? Why?</h3>
<p>Ans.	Adventure is the thrill of doing something out of the ordinary. It reduces the melancholy of an individual. Many prefer to go on a solo trip while others don't mind the company of their friends and family members. Megan Leung, a nature lover, had a courage to undertake a solo adventurous journey.
    Leung spent five-week long walk along the western Himalayas. In the travelogue, entitled 'Discovering West Nepal The Wild Frontier', the writer recounts her experiences of discovering westem Nepal. Her journey featured travels to Annapurna and Dhaulagiri circuit. She scaled up a long distance on foot, with her courage as her sole partner. On the way, she had to address the challenges of very dangerous passes, like Jang La Pass. Other rocky and snowy cliffs also posed countless threats to her. However, other natural forces, like birds, lakes and mountains, kept encouraging her all along. The fearless traveller treated all the challenges with a strong courage and persisted on her journey. To speak the truth, the journey was adventurous and heroic.
    </p>

<h2>Writing</h2>
<h3>A.	Write a travelogue of your recent visit to a natural/religious place in about 300 words. Use the following clues.</h3>

<table>
    <tbody>
    <tr>
    <td width="585">
    <p><strong>Local costumes and traditions.... Cuisine ... Depiction of places of interest, local history and culture.... Your adventures...... Prices and transportation.... Entertainment</strong></p>
    </td>
    </tr>
    </tbody>
    </table>
    <p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>
    <p><strong>Travelogue</strong></p>
    <p><strong>Ans.</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; One of the beautiful places of Nepal is Mustang valley. Muktinath temple simply stands as the most special part of this place. Last month, I got a chance to pay a visit to this favourite tourist destination. In my company, there were other 20 enthusiastic youths. The 5-day tour started with our departure to Pokhara on a tourist bus from Kathmandu. The next day we took a mountain flight from Pokhara to Jomsom. We stayed a hotel and had Dal Bhat with Sukuti and Achar. Local brand of drinking was really pleasing. We spent night in a cozy room with a balcony. From where, we could see golden glory mountain in the easy sunshine. We had our breakfast in the balcony. We observed the snowy peak Himalayan near by the valley. The Mustang valley was really dry and windy at that point of time (October). We saw many rocks, passes and some deep patches of forest, apple orchards and green fields covered with peas and buckwheat. We came across many monasteries and people with prayer wheels. They were speaking Tibetan language and wearing Docha, Bakhu and had long scarps with fur around the neck.</p>
    <p>We took a Jeep to Muktinath Temple. It took us around 2 hours to reach the religious hub. The Jeep dropped us at a certain distance from the Temple and we had to walk the rest. We had to climb around 250-steps to reach the Temple. On reaching the Temple we felt worthy of all the breaks throughout the journey.</p>
    <p>The next day we visited Maharaini Pauwa in Kagbeni. Kagbeni is the confluence of Kaligandaki river and Kag Hhola or Kali Khola. One could find Saligrams (sacred stones) there. Hindus thronged in that place to worship them taking the same for a Hindu God God Bishnu. On day 5, we flew back to Pokhara and took a tourist bus to get back to Kathmandu. The 5-day tour costs us almost 2,50,000 (12, 000 per head).</p>
    <p>The journey to Mustang was quite pleasant. We were warmly welcomed by the local people. We got good hospitality in Jana Shanti School as well. It was an outstanding trip for my life..</p>


<h3>B.	Write an essay in about 500 words on 'Importance of Tourism in Nepal'.</h3>

<p><strong>Tourism in Nepal</strong></p>
<p>Simply putting, tourism is the activities of people traveling to and staying in places outside their usual environment for leisure, business or other purposes. Nepal is an all-time favourite tourist destination. It hosts a number of natural, and cultural beauties, gifts, resources and wonders. There are many places and things of cultural, historical and religious importance. Mt. Everest, the highest peak in the world gives the most significant audacity of all. The snow-capped mountain peaks, beautiful water resources, green forests, and mesmerizing flora and fauna add to this signatory position of this small nation.</p>
<p>Nepal has some strong potentialities in the field of tourism. Nature has given us many things which are liked by tourists. Some tourists come here to enjoy the wonders of nature Some of them visit our country for trekking and climbing mountains. Some want to learn something about our history, culture, religion and so on. We can see some tourists come to enjoy their holidays.</p>
<p>We can get many advantages from it. Firstly, we can earn foreign currency which can be used for our development. many people have got employed in the office belonging to tourism. Thus, it helps to reduce the problem of unemployment. Tourists buy native goods and articles of our country. Bas a result, our cottage industries can get benefit. Tourism promotes our hotel industries. Similarly, many tourists guide and porters also get employed. We can learn their language, culture and traditions from the tourists. They also leam many things from us. The fame of our nation gets widened. Our country will be known to all part of the world.</p>
<p>Tourism has brought some problems too. Some of the communicable diseases have been passed to the Nepalese citizens from the tourists. Furthermore, some of the beauty spots are getting polluted because of crowdedness. We can see many bottles, plastic bags, and other non-biodegradable wastes at the peak of the mountains and other tourist destinations. Some of the tourists can be criminals; they commit different anti-social activities and also badly influence innocent Nepalese people to get on the wrong tracks.</p>
<p>Some of the issues are hindering tourism development in Nepal. The major problems are transportation and security. Most of the scenes of beauty are in remote area. We have to build roads to go to these places. Yet we have to depend on air services only. Similarly, the problem of security has also reduced the number tourists. Not to forget that the tourists don't get proper accommodation in the rural areas of remote districts. We should work in unison to promote tourism in Nepal. All the concerned sectors should give equal attention to address tourism related issues.</p>

