<h2>Comprehension </h2>
<h3>Answer these questions.</h3>
<h3>a.	Why did the author feel that she was lucky to be so naïve of her freshman year at college?</h3>
<p>Ans.	The author felt that she was lucky to be so naive of her freshman year at college because she didn't know what exactly she didn't know. She underwent her fist year being aware of the social currencies exchanged around her only dimly perceiving markers of wealth and status. </p>
<h3>b.	Why did she say that she went to college in the Stone Age?</h3>
<p>Ans.	The writer said that she went to college in the Stone Age because there was not as advanced technological innovation in her time as it is in her son's college year. There had been typewriters and carbon paper, telephone with curly cords, TVs with a few channels without remotes and cassette tapes. Compared to Hayden's day, there were not many gadgets. Internet was still in the womb. She had to read volumes of books and listen to the lectures and note down.</p>
<h3>c.	What kinds of technological tools can Hayden use at his college life unlike at his mother's time? </h3>
<p>Ans.	Hayden can use technology in almost everything. He carries out both large and small chores with the help of it. He installed Yale-specific apps on his phone that provide information about when the washers and dryers in the basement of hist dorm are available, the daily menus of each dining hall, ratings of local restaurant, student contact information, the entire list of classes and interactive campus map, that shows him where he is and where he is going.</p>
<h3>d.	How has the internet and social sites affected the lifestyle of the youths? </h3>
<p>Ans.	The internet and social sites have largely impacted the life style of youth. Within few minutes one can gather any amount of information about anyone through social networking sites like Facebook, Twitter and Instagram. Soon after arriving on campus, they make a spread sheet of potential classes, vetting them in advance by using teacher rating sites and watching videos of potential professors on YouTube. However, these technological innovations are not problem-free; in their presence, the youths will face many obstacles in practical life and the tendency to ignore the social norms and values will increase among them.</p>
<h3>e.	What things about college life will Hayden really miss unlike his mother? </h3>
<p>Ans.	She suspects that Hayden will miss trekking all the way across campus on a snowy day to a friend's dorm room only to find that person gone but another roommate available, and making new friend in the process. Moreover, he won't have to type and retype his papers for revisions finding in that process new insights into what he is written. He will also not have the luxury of being in the common room at 9 p.m. every Sunday to watch a specific TV show.</p>

<h3>f.	The writer says, "I worry that students today are more connected and more fragmented". Isn't this paradoxical? How?</h3>
<p>Ans.	Yes, the writer sounds quite paradoxical and sarcastic in this statement. The modern students are connected with people via internet, and social networking sites. In the process, they get fragmented with professors, books, and insightful knowledge. They are overwhelmingly gadget conscious. They give priority to virtually backed up distant relations rather than enjoying the company of their family members and relatives They will slowly ignore familial and societal norms and values. More clearly speaking, they will be more mechanical rather than social.</p>


<h2>Critical thinking</h2>

<h3>a.Do you think that advancements of technology can hinder the exposure students receive in school, and block them from gaining some of life's most memorable moments? Give reasons in support of your answer. </h3>
<p>Ans. Advancements of technology can enrich a pupil's life in many ways. When students are using technology as a tool or a support for learning with others, they are in an active role rather than the passive role of recipient of information transmitted by teacher, textbook or broadcast. They are actively making choices about how to generate, obtain, manipulate or display information. Technology use allows many more. Besides, they are thinking proactively about information, making choices, and executing skills than is typical in teacher led-sessions. Moreover, when technology is used as a tool to support learners in performing authentic tasks, the students are in position of defining their goals, making design of decisions and evaluating their progress. Education technology can make learning more interactive and collaborative. This can help the students to engage with course materials more effectively. They learn by doing instead of memorizing facts from books.</p>
<p>But the advantages of technological advancement should not mask the drawbacks of the same. For instance, the learners miss the real experience of life and cognitive power to acquire knowledge.</p>
<p>They may lose their analytical innate knowledge if they do not interact with teacher or friends. They may not be familiar with textbook and its theme.</p>
<p>In my opinion, we must consider both of the above-stated perspectives while meditating on the issue of our discussion.</p>

<h3>b.	Kline's essay focuses on the contrast between her son's freshman college experience and her own, but she also establishes what they have in common. Explain.</h3>
<p>Ans.	Kline's essay focuses on contrast between her son's freshman college experience and her own. In her time, there weren't many facilities in the college. She was unaware of the social currencies being exchanged around her. He had never seen fanciest car and she felt hesitation to ask the way around the college periphery. There only were typewriter, carbon papers telephone with curly curds and T.V. with a few channels and no remotes. But her son was very lucky. Because he has internet facilities. He can search route of the campus area in google map. Every room, timetable and reading class are exposed in the net. He could make friends within a minute. Hayden can get every information in Internet He has laptop, computer, iPad, smart and phone. He is familiar with digital era.</p>
<p>However, the mother and the son have some things in common as well. The first similarity is that both of them are first-year students at university. Their college is also same. He is also away from his hometown for study like his mother. The rooms of the college, physical appearance, playground and blocks of college are same. All the students are unfamiliar. Like his mother, he doesn't have any experience of college life. </p>
<h3>c.	Has internet aided to broadening or narrowing the critical thinking capacity of youths or readers? How?</h3>
<p>Ans.	Internet has proved boon to us in some regards. One of such fascinating usages of this technological innovation is boosting of critical thinking Plainly stating, critical thinking is the ability to carefully evaluate and think about the information presented to us. Correct facts foster one's critical thinking level. The ability to fact check is much easier with the internet than without. Furthermore, it allows students to look beyond the four walls of the classroom. They become highly critical of the information they receive. They analyze information. They even challenge the ideas given by their teachers or elders. They can critique their own knowledge too.</p>
<p>Moreover, they can learn new perspectives of looking at a problem. They can grasp more than their textbook can teach. In this regard, internet has aided to broadening and enhancing the critical thinking capacity of readers.</p>

