    <h2>Understanding the text</h2>
    <h3>Answer these questions</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>a.	Where did the narrator and his servant make forcible entrance?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The narrator and his servant Pedro made a forcible entrance into a desolate chateau, which was located in the Apennines of central Italy. The narrator was seriously wounded. His valet didn't want the narrator to stay in an open air. Hence, they entered inside the chateau without anyone's permission.<br><br>
        <strong>b.	Which special picture did the narrator notice in the room? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The narrator noticed an oval-shaped picture of a young girl in the room when the rays of candelabrum fell on it. The lifelike painting drew his attention.<br><br>
        <strong>c.	Describe the portrait that the narrator saw in the room.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The portrait that the narrator saw in the room was artistic and life-like. The injured visitor saw it when the rays of candelabrum fell on it. The oval-shaped portrait contained a beautiful picture of a young girl. Its frame was richly decorated. The young girl seemed just ripening into womanhood. The narrator found the lady's shoulder, and head, with radiant hair, so real. The brush work of tints into the portrait was elegant. He was overwhelmed by the magnificence of the mysterious piece of art. He described it as a "vignette" painted "much in the style of the favourite heads of Sully."<br><br>
        <strong>d.	What is the relationship between the portrait painter and its subject?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The relationship between the portrait painter and its subject is husband and wife. The husband of the subject (lady) is a passionate painter who has painted his wife's portrait. The painting took many weeks to complete.<br><br>
    </p>
    <h2>Reference to the context</h2>
    <p>
        <strong>a.	What is the central theme of the story? Who is the woman depicted in the oval portrait?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The central theme of the story "The Oval Portrait' is the relationship between life and art. This story has shown the destructive power of art and love. The woman depicted in the story is the wife the passionate painter.<br><br>
        <strong>b.	"The Oval Portrait" is a short horror story by Edgar Allan Poe involving the disturbing circumstances surrounding a portrait in a chateau. Elaborate.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>"The Oval Portrait' is a short classic western horror story, by the father of modern horror literature, Edgar Allan Poe. Known as the master of American Gothic literature, Poe composed numerous dark and mysterious poems and stories, including The Raven, The Black Cat and The Fall of the House of Usher. "The Oval Portrait' was first was first published the 1845 issue of The Broadway Journal. Having a Gothic undertone, the story magnificently explores a complex relation between art and life. Themes of death, hopelessness, dark and gloomy tone, madness and Gothic setting gives Poe's story a horror tale.<br><br>This story makes a portrait its chief subject matter of horror. The picture appears in one of the darker corners of the mysterious room. The psychic narrator cannot tell with certainty when www.ceram whether it is an image or a real-living person. The real taste of horror overtakes the readers when we are told that the portrait was the outcome of an obsessive painter, who compelled his wife to die for the creation of the painting. This young subject of the portrait with an extraordinary look is said to have been sitting for the painter in the dark, high turret-chamber and gaining paleness to her face before she sacrifices her life for her husband. <br><br>
        <strong>c.	"The Oval Portrait" suggests that the woman's beauty condemns her to death. Discuss.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>"The Oval Portrait magnificently explores a complex relation between art and life. Poe's tale brings about the themes, like obsession, art, life, and woman's beauty. By showing the death of a girl, owing to her excessive beauty, the writer argues that her beauty is to be blamed for the casualty.<br><br>
        <strong>d.	Discuss the story as a frame narrative (a story within a story).</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>"The Oval Portrait' is a frame story (story-within-story). Poe has served the two parallel tales in this story. The bigger story or the outermost story retells the narrative of the narrator, who was badly injured because of some unspecified reason, and his manservant, Pedro, make a forcible entrance into an abandoned chateau in the Apennines, a mountain range in central Italy. Similarly, the art book's writer's narrative, the inner story, focuses on the painter and its subject. The author tells how a naturally cheerful maiden of rarest beauty married a painter who was extraordinarily passionate about art.<br><br>
        <strong>e.	The story is told in a descriptive style, with plenty of imagery and symbolism. Which images and symbols do you find in the story? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>We can trace various images and symbols in the story. The abandoned chateau, the night setting and the mysterious painting are the images of Gothic tone. The young girl is the symbol of an innocent victim. Similarly, the painter is the symbol of obsession. He is also the image of a vampire. The portrait is the symbol of immortality of art.<br><br>
        <strong>f.	What does the expression "She was dead!" mean? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The expression signifies the painter's shocking realization about his subject's death. He exclaims because of her unexpected demise at the hand of his obsession and passion. He had brought a life into death for the sake of art. By using capital A in art, Poe has personified the lifeless art, in the process, giving it higher position than life.<br><br>
    </p>
    <h2>Reference bryond the text</h2>
