    <h2>Understanding the text</h2>
    <h3>Answer these questions.</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>a.	 Why did Jonathan think of himself as 'extraordinarily lucky'?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Jonathan thought of himself as extraordinarily lucky because he survived the Nigerian civil war along with most of his family members,<br><br>
        <strong>b.	What are the ‘five blessings' for which Jonathan is grateful? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Jonathan is grateful for the five blessings: his wife, three children, and his bicycle.<br><br>
        <strong>c.	Why did Jonathan mistrust the officer who wanted to take his bicycle? What does this tell you about the situation in Nigeria? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Jonathan mistrusted the officer who wanted to take his bicycle because the officer easily accepted a bribe in exchange for his bicycle. The policeman, who could not remain untouched by poverty, was not sincere and firm either. It tells us about poverty, corruption and insecurity in Nigeria.<br><br>
        <strong>d. What visitors might be at the door? Are Jonathan and his wife completely surprised? Explain.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The unknown visitors might be the people who had come to rob Jonathan as they might have known about the egg-rasher. The protagonist and his wife are not completely surprised as they have heard about a recent robbery of a commoner in their town.<br><br>
        <strong>e.	Why does no one in the neighbourhood respond when the thieves pound on Jonathan's door? Why do the thieves call for the police?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>No one in the neighbourhood responds when the thieves pound on Jonathan's door for fear of their lives. The thieves called for the police because they knew that the terror-stricken neighbours would not turn up to support Jonathan's family. They wanted to make fun of the sufferers' appeal.<br><br>
    </p>
    <h2>Reference to the context</h2>
    <p>
        <strong>a.	What does Jonathan mean by his expression "Nothing puzzles God"? What does this expression reveal about his character? Explain by citing details from the story.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>'Nothing puzzles God is a refrain in Achebe's story 'Civil Peace'. Jonathan repeats this statement four times. The protagonist's catchphrase reflects his ability to move forward without being consumed by darkness. Moreover, it indicates his deep religious faith in God. It also shows his optimism and hope. Accordingly, God is everywhere and He is not surprised by anything. To conclude, this phrase refers to the gains. losses, and value of life. This expression establishes Achebe's main character as a fatalistic and hopeful person. He hopes for better tomorrow rather than mourning the losses in the past.<br><br><br>
        <strong>b.	How does Jonathan change as he experiences the conflicts in his life? Explain. </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Jonathan is a movable character. His personality changes as much as he encounters bitter experiences during the Nigerian Civil War. To be honest, the conflict turns him into a hopeful, peace-loving and hardworking man. He maintains cool composure during the adverse time. Besides, he prioritizes his family and work to the lamentation of losses. <br><br><br>
        <strong>c.	Read the extract and answer the questions below. <br>"To God who made me; if you come inside and find one hundred pounds, take it and shoot me and shoot my wife and children. I swear to God. The only money I have in this life is this twenty pounds egg-rasher they gave me today…”</strong><br><br>
        <strong>i.	Who is the speaker?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Jonathan is the speaker.<br><br>
        <strong>ii. Who is the speaker talking to?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>He is talking to the thieves.<br><br>
        <strong>iii. Who does "they" refer to?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>“They" refers to the government.<br><br><br>
        <strong>d.	Nigerian English has words like soja 'soldier' and katakata 'confusion', 'trouble' derived apparently from English words but transformed by native languages' phonologies. What does the author's use of dialect here add to the story?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Achebe uses Nigerian English to present the original African voice. By focusing on the native language, he attempts to promote local dialects. In the process, he raises a strong voice in preserving African cultural heritage. The dialects also help to present the actual character and life of Nigeria. In this regard, the writer seems to maintain his patriotic stance in his writing.<br><br><br>
        <strong>e.	Why do you think the thieves who come to rob Jonathan speak English with at heavier African accent than Jonathan does?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The thieves who come to rob Jonathan speak English with a heavier African accent than Jonathan does. The first reason for such differences may be the fact that Jonathan is more educated and civilized than the former group. Similarly, heavy African accent advocates for true Africanis, as the use of broken English accurately reflects eastern Nigerian society. Moreover, by giving more privilege to African dialect, the writer attempts to set up superiority and powerfulness of African culture. Such usage arouses comic effects too. <br><br><br>
        <strong>f.	The title of the story "Civil Peace" itself is ironical as there is little to differentiate "civil peace' from 'civil war'. Do you think that the title of this story is appropriate, or would "Civil War" have been a better title? Explain.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Achebe's story demonstrates the similarities between Nigeria during the Civil War and after the War. The title of the story is quite ironic since the setting is still full of violence and disorder. I think the title of the story is suitable. It is because the writer's argument becomes much clearer and sharper with the use of ironic rather than a dull straightforward title. Additionally, the writer has focused on the optimistic future rather than the tragic past in the story. To present ‘hope’, ‘peace’ will be a better term than ‘war’. To sum up, the sarcastic topic is quite appropriate to highlight the violence still present in post-war Nigeria.<br><br>
    </p>
    <h2>Reference beyond the text</h2>
    <p>
        <strong>a.	How would you describe the civil peace in Nigeria?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>'Civil Peace brings to the fore the absence of civility in post-war Nigeria. Moreover, the situation of the Civil peace in Nigeria wasn't up to the mark yet. People still lived-in fear as they had to face various problems after the war. Corruption and theft were still prevalent. The government had failed to maintain rule of law as well as peace and order in the society.<br><br>
        <strong>b.	What kind of attitude towards life do you think you would have if your situation was similar to that of Jonathan's?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>If I was in a similar situation to that of Achebe's protagonist, I would be desperate and hopeless. I would have gone far away from the war-affected region to save me and my family. I would not have the courage of Jonathan. <br><br>
        <strong>c.	Draw the character sketch of Jonathan Iwegbu.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Jonathan Iwegbu is the lead character of Achebe's short story. He has survived the Nigerian civil war, along with his wife and three of his four children. In the present, he faces the uncertain future with enthusiastic optimism. He gives thanks for what he has rather than regret what he has lost. He counts all the blessings he has been given, chief among them his family, and after that, his scant material possessions, his bicycle and his home. He uses these possessions to immediately begin rebuilding his life, the bicycle becomes a taxi, and the house becomes a bar. The one thing that Jonathan cannot cast a positive light on is the thieves' assault; however, he still never complains about losing twenty pounds, a significant sum. Instead, the next moming finds Jonathan, and his family, hard at work again, already looking ahead to the future. In this way, the writer has portrayed Jonathan as a positive character.<br><br>
    </p>
