    <h2>Understanding the text</h2>
    <h3>Answer these questions.</h3>
    <p>
        <strong>a. How does the astrologer's appearance help him attract customers? How does he help the customers
            satisfy their needs? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The astrologer's forehead is covered with sacred ash and vermilion. He wears a
        saffron-coloured turban on his head. His eyes sparkles abnormally which is the result of continually looking for
        clients and customers. The power of his eyes to attract people is also due to their positioning between dark
        whiskers and a painted forehead. He helps the customers satisfy their needs with his working analysis of their
        troubles like marriage, money, etc. He is able to please them because of his clever guessing.<br><br>
        <strong>b. How do you characterise the astrologer's attitude toward the stranger? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The astrologer is calm, observant and deceptive character. When he is about to wind up his
        business, he meets a rogue character, Guru Nayak who is a part of his past life. The astrologer sees the
        stranger before him and takes him to be his possible customer. <br><br>
        <strong>c. What details does the astrologer give the stranger about his past? </strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>He tells the visitor that he was stabbed by a knife and thrown into a well to die, and
        some passers-by saw him and saved from dying. <br><br>
        <strong>d. Why does he advise the stranger to go home immediately?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>The astrologer tells the stranger to take the next train to home and do never venture into
        town again. He gives this piece of advice as a means of self-preservation. He recognizes the newcomer as the man
        he tried to kill after a drunken quarrel decades ago. <br><br>
        <strong>e. What is your reaction to the conversation between the astrologer and his wife?</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>I feel quite pleased at the astrologer getting rid of his guilt and fear. Moreover, he had
        managed to earn a little extra money that day.<br><br>
    </p>
    <h2>Reference to the context</h2>
    <p>
        <strong>a. Suspense is the feeling of anticipation you may have as you read. In this story, what details
            contributed to your feelings of suspense and surprise? Explain.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>This is a suspenseful story. We can trace out some elements of suspense in the narrative.
        The feeling of suspense is created about the personal and past life of the astrologer. The reader is told that
        he was not intended to be an astrologer. He left his village without any previous plan. The reader is also told
        that astrology is not his family business. This creates curiosity in the mind of the reader about the reason why
        he broke this ancestral cycle and was forced him to leave his home all of a sudden. The sense of suspense
        continues with the astrologer's encounter with the stranger. The astrologer catches a glimpse of the stranger's
        face in the flash of light created by the matchstick, and immediately disagrees to accept the stranger's
        challenge. At the end of the story, the reader is surprised with revelation of the fact that the astrologer was
        the person who stabbed the stranger and left for dead when he was drunk during one of his days as a
        youngster.<br><br><br>
        <strong>b. Analyse the conflicts in "An Astrologer's Day." Explain how the conflicts are resolved and what they
            reveal about the characters involved in the story.</strong><br>
        <strong>Ans. </strong>Conflict is the problem that the characters face throughout the story that keeps the plot
        moving. It allows us to go deep inside the characters and relate to how they feel and problem they face.
        <br><br>Both internal and external conflicts can be noticed in the story. The first conflict occurs when a
        stranger appears in the scene as the astrologer's client. The astrologer is packing up his stuff and ready to
        call it a day. The stranger challenges. the fortune teller to provide specific answers for his questions. As the
        stranger lights his cheroot, he catches a glimpse of his face by the match light and for some unclear reasons
        the astrologer feels uncomfortable and rejects the challenge. But he is forced to tell the stranger something
        that will satisfy him. The stranger is surprised to be told about his past life by the astrologer, and agrees to
        give up his search for his enemy who was declared to have been crushed under a lorry. The astrologer ensures a
        safe and secure life for himself hereafter.<br><br><br>
        <strong>c. "All right. I will speak. But will you give me a rupee if what I say is convincing? Otherwise I will
            not open my mouth, and you may do what you like." </strong><br>
