<h1>Chapter 2
    <br>
A Sunny Morning   
</h1>

<i>Serafin and Joaquin Alvarez Quintero 
    (Translated from the Spanish by Lucretia Xavier Floyd)
    </i>
<h2>Before Reading</h2>
<h2>Answer these questions.</h2>
<h3>a. Have you ever had an unexpected meeting with someone in a park? </h3>
<p>Ans. I have had such an experience. Three years before I accidentally encountered my English teacher in the UN Park. He was there with his wife and children. 1 blushed at the sight of him.</p>

<h3>b. How do your expectations influence the way you interact with others? </h3>

<p>All of us have got expectations. They are the part of our disposition. A positive expectation marks a superior personality. Our expectations influence everything. including interaction with others. If we are going to get benefitted from the person we are communicating, we are likely to be more cordial and diplomatic.</p>

<h3>c.How have unexpected encounters in your life sometimes turned out to be rewarding?  </h3>
<p>Unexpected encounters can be rewarding sometimes. Once I came across a girl from my previous class in a park. We rarely conversed at school. We had a grand conversation on that day. We have become very good friends since then.</p>
<br>

<img src="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/iampokharasahitey/englishapp/main/class11section5chapter2img1.jpg">
<p>Serafin Álvarez Quintero (1871-1938) and Joaquin Alvarez Quintero (1873-1944) were
    Spanish dramatists. They grew up in Utrera, a small town near Seville in the region of
    Spain called Andalusia. They began writing for the theatre at a young age. They were
    popularly known as the Golden Boys of the Madrid theatre.
    They collaborated in almost 200 dramas depicting the life,
    manners, and speech of Andalusia.
    </p>

<P>Their first stage piece, Gili to, was written in 1889. Among the
    brothers' best-known works are the comedies The Flowers
    (1901). A Sunny Morning (1905), and The Merry Heart (1906), as well as the uncharacteristically serious Malvaloca (1912). Several of their plays were translated into English by Helen and Harley Granville-Barker (1927-32). Their complete collection of plays was published in seven volumes as Obras Completas in the early 1950s.
    </P>
<p>A Sunny Morning is a light comedy that narrates the reunion of two lovers now in their
    70s meeting at a park who in their youth were passionate lovers but torn apart by the
    cruelty of fate. The setting of this play is a sunny morning in Madrid, Spain on a bench in
    the park.
    </p>
<h2>Understanding the text</h2>
<h3>Answer the following questions. </h3>
<h3>a. What makes Dona Laura think that Don Gonzalo is an ill-natured man? Why do neither Dona Laura nor Don Gonzalo reveal their true identities?</h3>
<p>Ans.Don Gonzalo approaches Laura as he shares her bench. She gets angry as the old man tries to scare the pigeons. She calls him "an ill-natured man" for his insensitive act, Despite the fact that they came to know about each other in reality, they do not want to reveal their true identities, for they have lost their charming youth.</p>
<h3>b. At what point of time, do you think, Laura and Gonzalo begin to recognise
    each other?
    </h3>
<p>When Dona Laura takes the book from Don Gonzalo and reads aloud, "Twenty Years Pass, both of them begin to recognize each other.</p>

<h3>c. When does Dona Laura realise that Don Gonzalo was her former lover?</h3>
<p>When Don Gonzalo reads verses from the poet Campoamor's 'Twenty years pass", Dona Laura realises that the old man was her former lover</p>

<h3>d. Why do Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo spin fictitious stories about themselves?</h3>
<p>They spin fictitious stories where Laura identifies herself as the friend of the Silver
    Maiden while he identifies himself as the cousin of Don Gonzalo. They create fictional stories to fool each other so that they could continue on a new discovery of happiness. Actually, they fear that it might be embarrassing to know about each other in real. 
    </p>
<h3>e.  How do Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo feel about each other?</h3>
<p>They are overjoyed at the presence of each other. At the end of the play, they change their attitude and build a very positive romantic feeling. They are happier
    for this unexpected encounter.
    </p>

<h2>Reference to the context</h2>
<h3>a. Look at the extract below and answer the questions that follow:
    "Yes, you are only twenty. (She sits down on the bench.) Oh, I feel more tired
    today than usual. (Noticing Petra, who seems impatient.) Go, if you wish to chat with your guard."
    </h3>
<pre>
i. Who is the speaker? 
Ans. Dona Laura is the speaker.
ii. Who does 'you' refer to?
Ans. "You' refers to Petra.
iii. Who is the "guard' the speaker is talking to?
Ans. The guard is the boyfriend of Petra who also guards the park.
    
</pre>

<h3>b. Read the extract dialogue from the play and answer the questions that follow:</h3>
<pre>
DONA LAURA: (Indignantly.) Look out!
DON GONZALO: Are you speaking to me, senora?
DONA LAURA: Yes, to you.
DON GONZALO: What do you wish?
DONA LAURA: You have scared away the birds who were feeding on my crumbs.
DON GONZALO: What do I care about the birds?
DONA LAURA: But I do. DON GONZALO: This is a public park.   
</pre>

<h3>c. Who is Dona addressing by saying "Look out"?</h3>
<p>Ans. She is addressing Don Gonzalo. </p>

<h3>d. What was Dona doing?</h3>
<p>Ans. She was feeding the pigeons. </p>

<h3>e. Who scared the birds? Are they pet birds? </h3>
<p>Ans. Don Gonzalo scared the birds. They are not pet birds. </p>

<h3>f. Where are at the time of the conversation?</h3>
<p>The speakers are at a park in Madrid, the capital of Spain.</p>


<h3>g. What is the effect of flashback in the play when Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo
    knew that they were the lovers in the past?
    </h3>
<p>Ans. Serafin and Joaquin Alvarez Quintero have used the flashback technique in their play to the perfection. Recollection of the cordial romantic moments adds fragrance to their present friendship. This, in turn, paves the way for Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo's newly discovered joy. In short, this sort of remembrance thrills the veteran souls under discussion as they rediscover their youthful passion for romance.</p>

<h3>h. Discuss how the play is built around humour and irony. </h3>

<p>Ans. A Sunny Morning' is a humorous one-act play by two Spanish playwrights, Serafin and Joaquin Alvarez Quintero. The writing duos retell a romantic tale, utilizing humour and irony as the chief literary devices. We can trace the element of humour from the beginning of the play. The little quarrels between the two elders set the comic tone of the play. The comic sense of Laura is admirable. ciders set up when she quips at Gonzalo's walking. "A carriage would not raise more dust than his feet." Her words create such ringing laughter that they are delectable. When she asks him, "Do you use your handkerchief as a shoe brush?" adds to the perfect m. Do you timing of comedy. </p>
<p>When it comes to irony, we can catch some deliberate efforts of the characters to
    hide or misinterpret truth. It is ironical that they do not want to disclose their
    identities, for they fear that their unpleasantly changed looks could be deterrents in their newly found joy.
    </p>

<h3>i. How is the title 'A Sunny Morning' justifiable? Discuss.</h3>
<p>"A Sunny Morning' is a one-act play by two Spanish playwrights, Serafin and Joaquin Alvarez Quintero. Set in a park in Madrid on a sunny autumn morning, the play narrates the reunion of two lovers, Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo, now in their
    70s meeting at a park who in their youth were passionate lovers but torn apart by
    the cruelty of fate.
    </p>

<p>The title of the play coheres the theme of the text. Simply keeping, the drama comes with youthful romance of the lead characters' past and romantic aspects of love in the guise of new friendship. Moreover, their relation has started shining. They are as bright and colourful as the rays of sunlight. Since the playwrights intend to serve a perfect romantic reunion of the old lovers, the title does justice in
    giving the new -found relation a positive atmosphere.
    </p>

<h2>Reference beyond the text</h2>
<h3>a. What do you predict will happen in the next meeting between Dona Laura and
    Don Gonzalo? Discuss. 
    </h3>

<p>The playwrights have ended the play with a positive note. We can expect more frequent friendly meetings between Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo from this setup. </p>

<h3>b. Was it wise for Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo to keep their identities secret? How might their secrets affect future meetings?</h3>

<p>I think, it was wise for Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo to keep their identities secret. They are enjoying talking to each other as the strangers. If the identity was revealed, they might have got surprised and embarrassed. Moreover, their reunion could have become tragic as well. Their secrets might hurt them in long run. Their future meetings might turn into more tragic gradually.</p>

<h3>c. Write the summary of the play.</h3>
<p>"A Sunny Morning' is a one-act play by two Spanish playwrights, Serafin and Joaquin Alvarez Quintero. Set in a park in Madrid on a sunny autumn moming, the play narrates the reunion of two lovers, Dona Laura and Don Gonzalo, now in their 70s meeting at a park who in their youth were passionate lovers but torn apart bythe cruelty of fate.</p>

<p>The drama begins with Dona Laura, a beautiful white-haired lady of about seventy, happily feeding pigeons in the park. Don Gonzalo, a gentleman of seventy, gouty and impatient, enters and, finding his favourite park bench occupied by the three priests, sits beside his lover from the past. Both of them visit the park regularly. being accompanied by their servants because of their old age. They are annoyed with each other as both want bench to themselves. Gonzalo rudely comments on as want her feeding the pigeons and starts reading his poems loudly. After asking her permission while reading from the poet Campo amor’s Twenty years pass, both feel that they were the lovers in the past. He tells her that he first met him in Valencia, a city in Spain, which also happens to be his native place. Surprisingly, Laura also tells him she had also Spent her youth at a villa called Maricela, not far from Valencia. Gonzalo who was also familiar with the villa asks if she a remembers a beautiful lady called Laura. She lies to him that the girl was her best friend. They talk about love-affair between the friend and a gallant lover. Gonzalo tells her that the follow was his cousin. When the girl was to be married off to a merchant, the lover duels with him, in the process wounding him badly, and runs off to Madrid. She waits for her lover to return but when he does not, marries the merchant after two years. Gonzalo tells her that his cousin joined the army and met with glorious death. Both realise that they are lying but pretend to be unaware. At the end of the play, both Laura and Gonzalo do not acknowledge who they really are and leave the park promising to meet the next day.</p>
<p>In this way, the playwright duos bring not only a comical side of a romantic
    relationship but also let us feel the pain of tragic separation.
    </p>


